{"title_page": "Janet Beaton", "text_new": "{{For|Janet Beaton, Countess of Arran|James Hamilton, 1st Earl of Arran}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name            =Janet Beaton\n|birth_date      =1519\n|birth_place     =Creich, [[Scotland]]\n|death_date      =January 1569 (aged 49-50)\n|death_place     =Scotland\n|nationality     =Scottish\n|known_for       =Mistress of [[James Hepburn, Earl of Bothwell]]; immortalised as [[Sir Walter Scott]]'s ''Wizard Lady of Branxholm'' in his narrative poem \"[[Lay of the Last Minstrel]]\"\n|spouse         ={{marriage|Sir James Crichton |1538|1539}}<br />{{marriage|Sir Simon Preston |1540|1543}}<br />{{marriage|Sir [[Walter Scott of Branxholme and Buccleuch]] |1544|1552}}\n|children           =Walter Scott<br>David Scott<br>Grisel Scott<br>Janet Scott<br>Margaret Scott\n|parents        =Sir John Beaton, 2nd Laird of Creich<br>Janet Hay\n|}}\n'''Janet Beaton''', Lady of Branxholme and Buccleugh (1519\u20131569) was an aristocratic Scottish woman and a mistress of [[James Hepburn, Earl of Bothwell]].<ref>Antonia Fraser, ''Mary, Queen of Scots'', p. 303</ref>\nShe had a total of five husbands. One of her nieces was [[Mary Beaton]], one of the four [[lady-in-waiting|ladies-in-waiting]] of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], known in history as the [[four Marys]]. In her lifetime, she was accused of having been a [[witch]].<ref>Fraser, pp. 303, 357</ref> Janet was immortalised as [[Sir Walter Scott]]'s ''Wizard Lady of Branxholm'' in his celebrated narrative poem \"[[Lay of the Last Minstrel]]\".<ref>Fraser, p. 303</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nJanet was born in 1519, one of the eleven children of Sir John Beaton, 2nd Laird of [[Creich Castle|Creich]] and Janet Hay, daughter of John Hay, [[Provost (civil)|provost]] of [[Dundee]] by his wife Elizabeth Crichton. Her father was the hereditary keeper of [[Falkland Palace]]. Her brother was [[Robert Beaton of Creich|Robert Beaton, 4th Laird of Creich]], and her sister, Elizabeth Beaton was a mistress of King [[James V of Scotland]], by whom she had an illegitimate daughter, Jean. Her niece was [[Mary Beaton]], one of the celebrated ladies-in-waiting of Mary, Queen of Scots, known as \"the four Marys\". Janet was also related to [[Cardinal David Beaton]] and Queen Mary's ambassador to France, [[James Beaton II|James Beaton, Archbishop of Glasgow]].<ref>Fraser, p. 37</ref>\n\n== Marriages and children==\nJanet married her first husband, Sir James Crichton of Cranston Riddell in 1538 when she was nineteen years of age. In 1540, a year after Sir James's death, she married Sir [[Simon Preston of Craigmillar|Simon Preston]] of [[Craigmillar Castle]]; they were divorced in 1543 on grounds of [[consanguinity]] and her own admitted adultery with her future third husband. Sometime before June 1544 Janet married, as his third wife, her paramour Sir [[Walter Scott of Branxholme and Buccleuch]], Chief of the [[Clan Scott]] (1495- 4 October 1552), by whom she had five children:\n* Walter Scott\n* David Scott\n* Grisel Scott (born 1552), married firstly, William Borthwick, 6th Lord Borthwick, by whom she had five sons; she married secondly, Walter Cairncross.\n* Janet Scott, married firstly John Cranstoun of Cranstoun, by whom she had issue; she married secondly, Robert Scott of Haining.\n* Margaret Scott, married Robert Scott of Thirlestane, by whom she had issue.\n\nIn 1550, Janet's husband Sir Walter was appointed [[Border Reivers|Warden of the Middle March]] and the following year, Warden and Justiciar of [[Liddesdale]].\nOn 4 October 1552, Sir Walter was killed in a skirmish in Edinburgh's High Street with members of his clan's rivals, the [[Clan Kerr]] who ran him through with swords. In 1558, Janet marched at the head of an armed party consisting of two hundred members of her clan to the Kirk of St. Mary of the Lowes in [[Yarrow]], where she knocked down the doors in an attempt to apprehend Sir Peter Cranstoun. Janet was brought before the Justice; however a warrant issued by the [[regent]] [[Marie of Guise]] brought the proceedings against her to a halt.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.james.com/border_scott |title=Border Clan Scott History and Genealogy |accessdate=2009-03-15}}</ref>\n\nJanet had a total of five husbands.<ref>Fraser, p. 303</ref>\n\n== Affair with Bothwell ==\nJanet had many love affairs throughout her life, the most significant of these began sometime around  the year 1558 with [[James Hepburn, Earl of Bothwell]]. He was twenty-four at the time<ref>Fraser, p.303</ref> and she was almost forty. Janet was described as having possessed \"an unfading beauty\", combined with audacity, determination and sexuality.<ref>Fraser, p. 303</ref> Her ageless beauty was attributed to Janet's practice of [[Magic (paranormal)|sorcery]],<ref>Fraser, ''p.303</ref> and it was rumoured that she and Bothwell may have gone through a form of \"hand-fasting\" ceremony.<ref>Fraser, p. 303</ref>\n\nJanet Beaton was immortalised by Sir Walter Scott in his narrative poem \"[[Lay of the Last Minstrel]]\" as ''Wizard Lady of Branxholm'',  who could '\"bond to her bidding the viewless forms of air\". Bothwell would go on to marry in 1566 Lady [[Jean Gordon, Countess of Bothwell|Jean Gordon]] a wealthy [[Scottish Highlands|Highlander]] heiress, the sister of the [[George Gordon, 5th Earl of Huntly|5th Earl of Huntly]]; immediately following his divorce from Jean in 1567, he became the third husband of Queen Mary of Scotland.\n\nIn 1567, following the murder of [[Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley]], Janet Beaton's name was written on a placard in [[Edinburgh]] accusing her of having used witchcraft to influence the queen in consenting to her second husband's murder by Bothwell and the other conspirators.<ref>Fraser, p.357</ref> The same sorcery perpetrated by Janet was allegedly used against Queen Mary which caused her to become enamoured of Earl Bothwell. At [[Dunbar Castle]], Janet was one of the three attendants of Queen Mary following the latter's abduction by Bothwell. The other two women were Bothwell's widowed sister, [[Jean Hepburn]], and Janet's younger sister [[Margaret Beaton]].\n\nJanet Beaton died in January 1568/9.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Scots Peerage|last=Paul |first=James Balfour|publisher=Douglas|year=1905|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9lNmAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=21 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nJanet's sister [[Margaret Beaton]], born about 1526, married Arthur Forbes, 4th Laird of Rires in the parish of [[Kilconquhar]] and had two sons with him before his death in 1586. She was one of the ladies of Mary, Queen of Scots. When the queen had gone into labour with her son [[James VI and I]] on 19 June 1566, Margaret bore her pains by proxy<ref>Roderick Graham, 'An Accidental Tragedy: The Life of Mary, Queen of Scots', Birlinn, 2012 https://books.google.co.uk/ Retrieved 12 November 2015</ref> and then acted as wet-nurse to the future king.<ref>P. G. Maxwell-Stuart, 'Satan's Conspiracy: Magic and Witchcraft in Sixteenth-century Scotland', Dundurn, 2001, p49. https://books.google.co.uk/ Retrieved 12 November 2015</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* Antonia Fraser, ''Mary, Queen of Scots'', Dell Publishing Co., Inc., New York, March 1971, originally published by Weidenfeld and Nicolson, London, 1969\n* Stirnet.com\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beaton, Janet}}\n[[Category:1519 births]]\n[[Category:1569 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:History of the Scottish Borders]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:People from Fife]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|Janet Beaton, Countess of Arran|James Hamilton, 1st Earl of Arran}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name            =Janet Beaton\n|birth_date      =1519\n|birth_place     =Creich, [[Scotland]]\n|death_date      =January 1569 (aged 49-50)\n|death_place     =Scotland\n|nationality     =Scottish\n|known_for       =Mistress of [[James Hepburn, Earl of Bothwell]]; immortalised as [[Sir Walter Scott]]'s ''Wizard Lady of Branxholm'' in his narrative poem \"[[Lay of the Last Minstrel]]\"\n|spouse         ={{marriage|Sir James Crichton |1538|1539}}<br />{{marriage|Sir Simon Preston |1540|1543}}<br />{{marriage|Sir [[Walter Scott of Branxholme and Buccleuch]] |1544|1552}}\n|children           =Walter Scott<br>David Scott<br>Grisel Scott<br>Janet Scott<br>Margaret Scott\n|parents        =Sir John Beaton, 2nd Laird of Creich<br>Janet Hay\n|}}\n'''Janet Beaton''', Lady of Branxholme and Buccleugh (1519\u20131569) was an aristocratic Scottish woman and a mistress of [[James Hepburn, Earl of Bothwell]].<ref>Antonia Fraser, ''Mary, Queen of Scots'', p. 303</ref>\nShe had a total of five husbands. One of her nieces was [[Mary Beaton]], one of the four [[lady-in-waiting|ladies-in-waiting]] of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], known in history as the [[four Marys]]. In her lifetime, she was accused of having been a [[witch]].<ref>Fraser, pp. 303, 357</ref> Janet was immortalised as [[Sir Walter Scott]]'s ''Wizard Lady of Branxholm'' in his celebrated narrative poem \"[[Lay of the Last Minstrel]]\".<ref>Fraser, p. 303</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nJanet was born in 1519, one of the eleven children of Sir John Beaton, 2nd Laird of [[Creich Castle|Creich]] and Janet Hay, daughter of John Hay, [[Provost (civil)|provost]] of [[Dundee]] by his wife Elizabeth Crichton. Her father was the hereditary keeper of [[Falkland Palace]]. Her brother was [[Robert Beaton of Creich|Robert Beaton, 4th Laird of Creich]], and her sister, Elizabeth Beaton was a mistress of King [[James V of Scotland]], by whom she had an illegitimate daughter, Jean. Her niece was [[Mary Beaton]], one of the celebrated ladies-in-waiting of Mary, Queen of Scots, known as \"the four Marys\". Janet was also related to [[Cardinal David Beaton]] and Queen Mary's ambassador to France, [[James Beaton II|James Beaton, Archbishop of Glasgow]].<ref>Fraser, p. 37</ref>\n\n== Marriages and children==\nJanet married her first husband, Sir James Crichton of Cranston Riddell in 1538 when she was nineteen years of age. In 1540, a year after Sir James's death, she married Sir [[Simon Preston of Craigmillar|Simon Preston]] of [[Craigmillar Castle]]; they were divorced in 1543 on grounds of [[consanguinity]] and her own admitted adultery with her future third husband. Sometime before June 1544 Janet married, as his third wife, her paramour Sir [[Walter Scott of Branxholme and Buccleuch]], Chief of the [[Clan Scott]] (1495- 4 October 1552), by whom she had five children:\n* Walter Scott\n* David Scott\n* Grisel Scott (born 1552), married firstly, William Borthwick, 6th Lord Borthwick, by whom she had five sons; she married secondly, Walter Cairncross.\n* Janet Scott, married firstly John Cranstoun of Cranstoun, by whom she had issue; she married secondly, Robert Scott of Haining.\n* Margaret Scott, married Robert Scott of Thirlestane, by whom she had issue.\n\nIn 1550, Janet's husband Sir Walter was appointed [[Border Reivers|Warden of the Middle March]] and the following year, Warden and Justiciar of [[Liddesdale]].\nOn 4 October 1552, Sir Walter was killed in a skirmish in Edinburgh's High Street with members of his clan's rivals, the [[Clan Kerr]] who ran him through with swords. In 1558, Janet marched at the head of an armed party consisting of two hundred members of her clan to the Kirk of St. Mary of the Lowes in [[Yarrow]], where she knocked down the doors in an attempt to apprehend Sir Peter Cranstoun. Janet was brought before the Justice; however a warrant issued by the [[regent]] [[Marie of Guise]] brought the proceedings against her to a halt.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.james.com/border_scott |title=Border Clan Scott History and Genealogy |accessdate=2009-03-15}}</ref>\n\nJanet had a total of five husbands.<ref>Fraser, p. 303</ref>\n\n== Affair with Bothwell ==\nJanet had many love affairs throughout her life, the most significant of these began sometime around  the year 1558 with [[James Hepburn, Earl of Bothwell]]. He was twenty-four at the time<ref>Fraser, p.303</ref> and she was almost forty. Janet was described as having possessed \"an unfading beauty\", combined with audacity, determination and sexuality.<ref>Fraser, p. 303</ref> Her ageless beauty was attributed to Janet's practice of [[Magic (paranormal)|sorcery]],<ref>Fraser, ''p.303</ref> and it was rumoured that she and Bothwell may have gone through a form of \"hand-fasting\" ceremony.<ref>Fraser, p. 303</ref>\n\nJanet Beaton was immortalised by Sir Walter Scott in his narrative poem \"[[Lay of the Last Minstrel]]\" as ''Wizard Lady of Branxholm'',  who could '\"bond to her bidding the viewless forms of air\". Bothwell would go on to marry in 1566 Lady [[Jean Gordon, Countess of Bothwell|Jean Gordon]] a wealthy [[Scottish Highlands|Highlander]] heiress, the sister of the [[George Gordon, 5th Earl of Huntly|5th Earl of Huntly]]; immediately following his divorce from Jean in 1567, he became the third husband of Queen Mary of Scotland.\n\nIn 1567, following the murder of [[Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley]], Janet Beaton's name was written on a placard in [[Edinburgh]] accusing her of having used witchcraft to influence the queen in consenting to her second husband's murder by Bothwell and the other conspirators.<ref>Fraser, p.357</ref> The same sorcery perpetrated by Janet was allegedly used against Queen Mary which caused her to become enamoured of Earl Bothwell. At [[Dunbar Castle]], Janet was one of the three attendants of Queen Mary following the latter's abduction by Bothwell. The other two women were Bothwell's widowed sister, [[Jean Hepburn]], and Janet's younger sister Margaret.\n\nJanet Beaton died in January 1568/9.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Scots Peerage|last=Paul |first=James Balfour|publisher=Douglas|year=1905|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9lNmAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=21 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nJanet's sister [[Margaret Beaton]], born about 1526, married Arthur Forbes, 4th Laird of Rires in the parish of [[Kilconquhar]] and had two sons with him before his death in 1586. She was one of the ladies of Mary, Queen of Scots. When the queen had gone into labour with her son [[James VI and I]] on 19 June 1566, Margaret bore her pains by proxy<ref>Roderick Graham, 'An Accidental Tragedy: The Life of Mary, Queen of Scots', Birlinn, 2012 https://books.google.co.uk/ Retrieved 12 November 2015</ref> and then acted as wet-nurse to the future king.<ref>P. G. Maxwell-Stuart, 'Satan's Conspiracy: Magic and Witchcraft in Sixteenth-century Scotland', Dundurn, 2001, p49. https://books.google.co.uk/ Retrieved 12 November 2015</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* Antonia Fraser, ''Mary, Queen of Scots'', Dell Publishing Co., Inc., New York, March 1971, originally published by Weidenfeld and Nicolson, London, 1969\n* Stirnet.com\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beaton, Janet}}\n[[Category:1519 births]]\n[[Category:1569 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:History of the Scottish Borders]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:People from Fife]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAffair with Bothwell:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Janet_Beaton"}
{"title_page": "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets", "text_new": "{{About|the book|the film|Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)|other uses|Chamber of Secrets (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|1998 fantasy novel by J. K. Rowling}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Good article}}{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name = Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets\n| author = [[J. K. Rowling]]\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| genre = [[Fantasy novel|Fantasy]]\n| publisher = {{ubl\n    |[[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]] (UK) (Canada 2010\u2013present)\n    |[[Arthur A. Levine Books|Arthur A. Levine]]/<br />[[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]] (US)\n    |[[Raincoast Books|Raincoast]] (Canada 1998\u20132010)\n    }}\n| isbn = 0-7475-3849-2\n| image = Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets.jpg\n| caption = Jacket art of the original UK edition\n| illustrator = [[Cliff Wright]] (UK Edition)<br />Jonny Duddle (2014 UK Edition)<br />[[Mary GrandPr\u00e9]] (US Edition)<br />[[Kazu Kibuishi]] (2013 US Edition)<br />Jim Kay (Illustrated edition)\n| series = ''[[Harry Potter]]''\n| release_number = {{ordinal|2}} in series\n| pub_date = 2 July 1998 (UK)<br />2 June 1999 (US)\n| pages = 251 (UK Edition)<br />360 (2014 UK Edition)<br />341 (US Edition)<br />368 (2013 US Edition)\n| preceded_by = [[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]\n| followed_by = [[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]\n}}\n\n'''''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets''''' is a [[fantasy novel]] written by British author [[J. K. Rowling]] and the second novel in the ''[[Harry Potter]]'' series. The plot follows [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry]]'s second year at [[Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry]], during which a series of messages on the walls of the school's corridors warn that the \"[[Chamber of Secrets]]\" has been opened and that the \"heir of [[Slytherin]]\" would kill all pupils who do not come from all-magical families. These threats are found after attacks that leave residents of the school petrified. Throughout the year, Harry and his friends [[Ron Weasley|Ron]] and [[Hermione Granger|Hermione]] investigate the attacks.\n\nThe book was published in the United Kingdom on 2 July 1998 by [[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]] and later in the United States on 2 June 1999 by [[Scholastic Inc]]. Although Rowling says she found it difficult to finish the book, it won high praise and awards from critics, young readers, and the book industry, although some critics thought the story was perhaps too frightening for younger children. Much like with other novels in the series, ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' [[Religious debates over the Harry Potter series|triggered religious debates]]; some religious authorities have condemned its use of magical themes, whereas others have praised its emphasis on self-sacrifice and the way one's character is the result of one's choices.\n\nSeveral commentators have noted that personal identity is a strong theme in the book and that it addresses issues of racism through the treatment of non-human, non-magical, and non-living people. Some commentators regard the diary as a warning against uncritical acceptance of information from sources whose motives and reliability cannot be checked. Institutional authority is portrayed as self-serving and incompetent.\n\nThe [[Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)|film adaptation of the novel]], released in 2002, became (at that time) the [[List of highest-grossing films|fifth highest-grossing film ever]] and received generally favourable reviews. Video games loosely based on ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' were also released for several platforms, and most obtained favourable reviews.\n\n==Plot==\n<!--\nThis Plot summary is unusually long. [[Talk:Harry_Potter_and_the_Chamber_of_Secrets/GA1]] explains what was included/excluded and how. If you want add content to the Plot summary:\n* Read [[Talk:Harry_Potter_and_the_Chamber_of_Secrets/GA1]] first.\n* Explain at [[Talk:Harry_Potter_and_the_Chamber_of_Secrets]] why making the Plot Summary longer is justified. If there's no explanation at [[Talk:Harry_Potter_and_the_Chamber_of_Secrets]], the addition to the Plot summary may be removed.\n-->\n]\n\n==Publication and reception==\n\n===Development===\nRowling found it difficult to finish ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' because she was afraid it would not live up to the expectations raised by ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]''. After delivering the manuscript to Bloomsbury on schedule, she took it back for six weeks of revision.<ref name=\"Sexton2007JKR\">{{cite book\n|last=Sexton|first=Colleen|title=J. K. Rowling|publisher=Twenty-First Century Books|year=2007|pages=77\u201378|chapter=Pottermania|isbn=0-8225-7949-9\n|url=https://books.google.com/?id=J_IPN8UMf7IC&pg=PA77&dq=%22Harry+Potter+and+the+Chamber+of+Secrets%22|accessdate=25 May 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nIn early drafts of the book, the ghost [[Nearly Headless Nick]] sang a self-composed song explaining his condition and the circumstances of his unknown death. This was cut because the book's editor did not care for the poem, which has been subsequently published as an extra on J. K. Rowling's official website.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/extrastuff_view.cfm?id=11|title=Nearly Headless Nick|last=Rowling|first=J.K.|accessdate=25 May 2009\n|year=2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423090611/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/extrastuff_view.cfm?id=11 <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=23 April 2009}}</ref> The family background of [[Dean Thomas (Harry Potter)|Dean Thomas]] was removed because Rowling and her publishers considered it an \"unnecessary digression,\" and she considered [[Neville Longbottom]]'s own journey of discovery \"more important to the central plot.\"<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/extrastuff_view.cfm?id=2\n|title=Dean Thomas's background (Chamber of Secrets)|last=Rowling|first=J.K.|accessdate=25 May 2009\n|year=2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502183210/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/extrastuff_view.cfm?id=2 <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=2 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Publication===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (US cover).jpg|thumb|upright|Original 1999 US cover of ''Chamber of Secrets''{{ffdc|1=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (US cover).jpg|log=2016 November 21}}]] -->\n''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' was published in the UK on 2 July 1998 and in the US on 2 June 1999.<ref name=\"Harry Potter UK Release Dates\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/235354|title=A Potter timeline for muggles|date=14 July 2007|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=27 September 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220001353/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/235354|archivedate=20 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Harry Potter US&nbsp;\u2014 Scholastic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scholastic.com/harrypotter/books/author/index.htm |title=Harry Potter: Meet J.K. Rowling |publisher=[[Scholastic Inc]] |accessdate=27 September 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106143234/http://www.scholastic.com/harrypotter/books/author/index.htm |archivedate=6 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It immediately took first place in UK bestseller lists, displacing popular authors such as [[John Grisham]], [[Tom Clancy]],<ref name=\"Sexton2007JKR\" /> and [[Terry Pratchett]]<ref>{{cite journal|date=25 August 1998|title=Digested read: Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets|journal=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1998/aug/25/booksforchildrenandteenagers|accessdate=25 May 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823162432/http://www.theguardian.com/books/1998/aug/25/booksforchildrenandteenagers|archivedate=23 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and making Rowling the first author to win the [[British Book Awards]] Children's Book of the Year for two years in succession.<ref name=\"Beckett2008Crossover\">{{cite book|last=Beckett|first=Sandra|title=Crossover Fiction|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=2008|pages=112\u2013115|chapter=Child-to-Adult Crossover Fiction|isbn=0-415-98033-X|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9ipnQ2ryU7IC&pg=PA114&lpg=PA114&dq=%22Harry+Potter+and+the+Philosopher%27s+Stone%22+book+sales+bestseller|accessdate=16 May 2009}}</ref> In June 1999, it went straight to the top of three US bestseller lists,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2003/jun/20spec1.htm|title=Harry Potter: The mania continues...|last=Pais|first=Arthur|date=20 June 2003|publisher=Rediff.com India Limited|accessdate=25 May 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210145751/http://www.rediff.com/news/2003/jun/20spec1.htm|archivedate=10 February 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> including in''The New York Times''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/99/06/20/bsp/fictioncompare.html|title=Best Sellers Plus|date=20 June 1999|work=The New York Times|accessdate=25 May 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20170429235628/https://www.nytimes.com/books/99/06/20/bsp/fictioncompare.html|archivedate=29 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFirst edition printings had several errors, which were fixed in subsequent reprints.<ref name=\"wsu\" /> Initially, Dumbledore said Voldemort was the last remaining [[ancestor]] of [[Salazar Slytherin]] instead of his descendant.<ref name=\"wsu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wsu.edu/~brians/errors/ancestor.html|title=Errors: Ancestor / Descendant|last=Brians|first=Paul|publisher=[[Washington State University]]|accessdate=25 May 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318214215/http://wsu.edu/~brians/errors/ancestor.html|archivedate=18 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Gilderoy Lockhart]]'s book on werewolves is entitled ''Weekends with Werewolves'' at one point and ''Wanderings with Werewolves'' later in the book.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rowling|first=J.K.|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets|publisher=Bloomsbury|location=London|year=1998| pages=38, 78|isbn=0-7475-3848-4}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' was met with near-universal acclaim. In ''[[The Times]]'', Deborah Loudon described it as a children's book that would be \"re-read into adulthood\" and highlighted its \"strong plots, engaging characters, excellent jokes and a moral message which flows naturally from the story\".<ref name=\"Loudon1998ReviewHPCSInTimes\">{{cite journal|last=Loudon|first=Deborah|date=18 September 1998|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets \u2013 Children's Books|journal=[[The Times]]|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/children/article778375.ece|accessdate=26 May 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530060229/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/children/article778375.ece|archivedate=30 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Fantasy author [[Charles de Lint]] agreed, and considered the second Harry Potter book to be just as good as ''Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone'', a rare achievement among series of books.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.sfsite.com/fsf/2000/cdl0001.htm|title=Books To Look For|last=de Lint|first=Charles|date=January 2000|accessdate=26 May 2009|publisher=Fantasy & Science Fiction|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123164104/http://www.sfsite.com/fsf/2000/cdl0001.htm|archivedate=23 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Thomas Wagner regarded the plot as very similar to that of the first book, based on searching for a secret hidden under the school. However, he enjoyed the parody of celebrities and their fans that centres round Gilderoy Lockhart, and approved of the book's handling of racism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfreviews.net/harrypotter2.html|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets|last=Wagner|first=Thomas|year=2000|accessdate=26 May 2009|publisher=Thomas M. Wagner|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105183909/http://www.sfreviews.net/harrypotter2.html|archivedate=5 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tammy Nezol found the book more disturbing than its predecessor, particularly in the rash behaviour of Harry and his friends after Harry withholds information from Dumbledore, and in the human-like behaviour of the [[Mandrake (mythology)|mandragora]]s used to make a potion that cures [[Petrifaction in mythology and fiction|petrification]]. Nevertheless, she considered the second story as enjoyable as the first.<ref name=\"NezolReviewAbout\">{{cite web|url=http://contemporarylit.about.com/od/fantasy/fr/harryPotter2.htm|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets)|last=Nezol|first=Tammy|publisher=About.com|accessdate=26 May 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522002803/http://contemporarylit.about.com/od/fantasy/fr/harryPotter2.htm|archivedate=22 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMary Stuart thought the final conflict with Tom Riddle in the Chamber was almost as scary as in some of [[Stephen King]]'s works, and perhaps too strong for young or timid children. She commented that \"there are enough surprises and imaginative details thrown in as would normally fill five lesser books.\" Like other reviewers, she thought the book would give pleasure to both children and adult readers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.curledup.com/chamber.htm|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets|last=Stuart|first=Mary|publisher=curledup.com|accessdate=26 May 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327142432/http://www.curledup.com/chamber.htm|archivedate=27 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to [[Philip Nel]], the early reviews gave unalloyed praise while the later ones included some criticisms, although they still agreed that the book was outstanding.<ref>{{cite book|last=Nel|first=Phillip|title=J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter novels: a reader's guide|publisher=Continuum International|year=2001|page=55|chapter=Reviews of the Novels |isbn=0-8264-5232-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qQYfoV62d30C&pg=PA54&dq=%22Harry+Potter+and+the+Chamber+of+Secrets%22|accessdate=26 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nWriting after all seven books had been published, [[Graeme Davis (mediaevalist)|Graeme Davis]] regarded ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' as the weakest of the series, and agreed that the plot structure is much the same as in ''Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone''. He described Fawkes's appearance to arm Harry and then to heal him as a ''[[deus ex machina]]'': he said that the book does not explain how Fawkes knew where to find Harry; and Fawkes's timing had to be very precise, as arriving earlier would probably have prevented the battle with the basilisk, while arriving later would have been fatal to Harry and Ginny.<ref name=\"bad\">{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Graeme|title=Re-Read Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets Today! an Unauthorized Guide|publisher=Nimble Books LLC|year=2008|page=1|chapter=Re-reading Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets|isbn=1-934840-72-6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mrvPPS5DXBEC&pg=PA2&dq=%22Harry+Potter+and+the+Chamber+of+Secrets%22|accessdate=25 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honours===\nRowling's ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' was the recipient of several awards.<ref name=\"levine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.arthuralevinebooks.com/book.asp?bookid=28|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets|date=2001\u20132005|publisher=Arthur A. Levine Books|accessdate=18 July 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060214085553/http://arthuralevinebooks.com/book.asp?bookid=28|archivedate=14 February 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[American Library Association]] listed the novel among its 2000 Notable Children's Books,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bookwizard.scholastic.com/tbw/viewBooklist.do?dp=%3D%3FUTF-8%3FB%3FYm9va2xpc3RJZD05OTg5OTcmc2hhcmVkPXRydWU%3D%3F%3D|title=ALA Notable Children's Books All Ages 2000|date=11 June 2007|publisher=[[Scholastic Inc.]]|accessdate=18 July 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716015006/http://bookwizard.scholastic.com/tbw/viewBooklist.do?dp=%3D%3FUTF-8%3FB%3FYm9va2xpc3RJZD05OTg5OTcmc2hhcmVkPXRydWU%3D%3F%3D|archivedate=16 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nas well as its Best Books for Young Adults.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/bestbooksya/2000bestbooks.cfm|title=Best Books for Young Adults|year=2000|publisher=[[American Library Association]]|accessdate=18 July 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090501061416/http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/bestbooksya/2000bestbooks.cfm <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=1 May 2009}}</ref> In 1999, [[Booklist]] named ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' as one of its Editors' Choices,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booklistonline.com/default.aspx?page=show_product&pid=3603404|title=Books for Youth \u2013 Fiction|last=Estes|first=Sally|author2=Susan Dove Lempke|year=1999|publisher=Booklist|accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref> and as one of its Top Ten Fantasy Novels for Youth.<ref name=\"levine\"/> The Cooperative Children's Book Center made the novel a CCBC Choice of 2000 in the \"Fiction for Children\" category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.education.wisc.edu/ccbc/books/hpreviews.asp|title=Harry Potter Reviews|year=2009|publisher=CCBC|accessdate=18 July 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610032311/http://www.education.wisc.edu/ccbc/books/hpreviews.asp|archivedate=10 June 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The novel also won Children's Book of the Year British Book Award,<ref name=\"NIBBY\"/> and was shortlisted for the 1998 Guardian Children's Award and the 1998 Carnegie Award.<ref name=\"levine\"/>\n\n''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' won the [[Nestl\u00e9 Smarties Book Prize]] 1998 Gold Medal in the 9\u201311 years division.<ref name=\"NIBBY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.raincoast.com/harrypotter/rowling.html|title=ABOUT J.K. ROWLING|year=2009|publisher=[[Raincoast Books]]|accessdate=18 July 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071221191008/http://www.raincoast.com/harrypotter/rowling.html |archivedate = 21 December 2007}}</ref> Rowling also won two other Nestl\u00e9 Smarties Book Prizes for ''Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone'' and ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]''. The [[Scottish Arts Council]] awarded their first ever Children\u2019s Book Award to the novel in 1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottisharts.org.uk/1/latestnews/1001908.aspx |title=Scottish Arts Council Children's Book Awards |date=30 May 2001 |publisher=[[Scottish Arts Council]] |accessdate=18 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081104022646/http://www.scottisharts.org.uk/1/latestnews/1001908.aspx |archivedate=4 November 2008 }}</ref> and it was also awarded Whitaker's Platinum Book Award in 2001.<ref name=\"levine\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/arts/2001/0921/harrypotter.html|title=Potter goes platinum|year=2009|website=RT\u00c9|accessdate=18 July 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050121192910/http://www.rte.ie/arts/2001/0921/harrypotter.html|archivedate=21 January 2005|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2003, the novel was listed at number 23 on the [[BBC]]'s survey [[The Big Read]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/bigread/top100.shtml \"BBC \u2013 The Big Read\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031065136/http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/bigread/top100.shtml |date=31 October 2012 }}. BBC. April 2003, Retrieved 12 December 2013</ref>\n\n==Main themes==\n''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' continues to examine what makes a person who he or she is, which began in the first book. As well as maintaining that Harry's identity is shaped by his decisions rather than any aspect of his birth,<ref name=\"NezolReviewAbout\" /><ref name=\"Jacobsen2004SecularCity\" /> ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' provides contrasting characters who try to conceal their true personalities: as Tammy Nezol puts it, Gilderoy Lockhart \"lacks any real identity\" because he is nothing more than a charming liar.<ref name=\"NezolReviewAbout\" /> Riddle also complicates Harry's struggle to understand himself by pointing out the similarities between the two: \"both half-bloods, orphans raised by [[Muggle]]s, probably the only two Parselmouths to come to Hogwarts since the great Slytherin.\"<ref name=\"Cockrell2004SecretPassword\">{{cite book\n|last=Cockrell |first=Amanda |title=The ivory tower and Harry Potter |editor-last=Whited |editor-first=L. |publisher=University of Missouri Press |year=2004 |pages=20\u201326 |chapter=Harry Potter and the Secret Password |isbn=0-8262-1549-1 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=iO5pApw2JycC&pg=PA15&dq=%22Harry+Potter+and+the+Chamber+of+Secrets%22 |accessdate=27 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nOpposition to class, death and its impacts, experiencing adolescence, sacrifice, love, friendship, loyalty, prejudice, and racism are constant themes of the series. In ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' Harry's consideration and respect for others extends to the lowly, non-human [[Dobby (Harry Potter)|Dobby]] and the ghost Nearly Headless Nick.<ref name=\"Knapp2003InDefenseOfHP\">{{cite journal|last=Knapp |first=Nancy |year=2003 |title=In Defense of Harry Potter: An Apologia |journal=School Libraries Worldwide |publisher=International Association of School Librarianship |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=78\u201391 |url=http://www.iasl-online.org/files/jan03-knapp.pdf |accessdate=14 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110309051050/http://www.iasl-online.org/files/jan03-knapp.pdf |archivedate=9 March 2011 }}</ref> According to Marguerite Krause, achievements in the novel depend more on ingenuity and hard work than on natural talents.<ref name=\"Krause2006EndOfReligion\">{{cite book |last=Krause |first=Marguerite |title=Mapping the world of Harry Potter |editor1-last=Lackey |editor1-first=M. |editor2-last=Wilson |editor2-first=L. |publisher=BenBella Books |year=2006 |pages=55\u201363 |chapter=Harry Potter and the End of Religion |isbn=1-932100-59-8 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=sKRkzVIK3foC&pg=PT12&dq=%22Harry+Potter+and+the+Chamber+of+Secrets%22 |accessdate=27 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nEdward Duffy, associate professor at [[Marquette University]], says that one of the central characters of ''Chamber of Secrets'' is Tom Riddle's enchanted diary, which takes control of Ginny Weasley \u2013 just as Riddle planned. Duffy suggests Rowling intended this as a warning against passively consuming information from sources that have their own agendas.<ref name=\"Duffy2002SentencesInHP\">{{cite journal|last=Duffy |first=Edward |year=2002 |title=Sentences in Harry Potter, Students in Future Writing Classes |journal=Rhetoric Review |publisher=Lawrence Erlbaum Associates, Inc. |volume=21 |issue=2 |pages=170\u2013187 |url=http://wrt-brooke.syr.edu/courses/205.03/rrhp.pdf |accessdate=27 May 2009 |doi=10.1207/S15327981RR2102_03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720053923/http://wrt-brooke.syr.edu/courses/205.03/rrhp.pdf |archivedate=20 July 2011 }}</ref> Although Bronwyn Williams and Amy Zenger regard the diary as more like an [[instant messaging]] or [[chat room]] system, they agree about the dangers of relying too much on the written word, which can camouflage the author, and they highlight a comical example, Lockhart's self-promoting books.<ref>{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Bronwyn|author2=Zenger, Amy|others=A.A.|title=Popular culture and representations of literacy|publisher=Routledge|year=2007|pages=113\u2013117, 119\u2013121|isbn=0-415-36095-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DDvbNnO4OH8C&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119&dq=%22chamber+of+secrets%22+riddle+identity|accessdate=27 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nImmorality and the portrayal of authority as negative are significant themes in the novel. Marguerite Krause states there are few absolute moral rules in Harry Potter's world, for example Harry prefers to tell the truth, but lies whenever he considers it necessary&nbsp;\u2013 very like his enemy [[Draco Malfoy]].<ref name=\"Krause2006EndOfReligion\" /> At the end of ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'', Dumbledore retracts his promise to punish Harry, Ron, and Hermione if they break any more school rules \u2013 after [[Professor McGonagall]] estimates they have broken over 100&nbsp;\u2013 and lavishly rewards them for ending the threat from the Chamber of Secrets.<ref>{{cite book |last=Rowling |first=J.K. |title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets |publisher=Bloomsbury |location=London |year=1998 |isbn=0-7475-3848-4 |chapter=Dobby's Reward |pages=241\u2013243}}</ref> Krause further states that authority figures and political institutions receive little respect from Rowling.<ref name=\"Krause2006EndOfReligion\" /> William MacNeil of Griffith University, Queensland, Australia states that the [[Minister for Magic]] is presented as a mediocrity.<ref>{{cite journal |last=MacNeil |first=William |year=2002 |title=\"Kidlit\" as \"Law-And-Lit\": Harry Potter and the Scales of Justice |journal=Law and Literature |publisher=University of California |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=545\u2013564 |url=http://www98.griffith.edu.au/dspace/bitstream/10072/6871/1/21489.pdf |accessdate=27 May 2009 |doi=10.1525/lal.2002.14.3.545 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005120036/http://www98.griffith.edu.au/dspace/bitstream/10072/6871/1/21489.pdf |archivedate=5 October 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In his article \"Harry Potter and the Secular City\", Ken Jacobson suggests the [[Ministry for Magic|Ministry]] as a whole is portrayed as a tangle of bureaucratic empires, saying that \"Ministry officials busy themselves with minutiae (e.g. standardising cauldron thicknesses) and coin politically correct euphemisms like 'non-magical community' (for Muggles) and 'memory modification' (for magical brainwashing).\"<ref name=\"Jacobsen2004SecularCity\">{{cite journal |last=Jacobsen |first=Ken |year=2004 |title=Harry Potter and the Secular City: The Dialectical Religious Vision Of J.K. Rowling |journal=Animus |volume=9 |pages=79\u2013104 |url=http://www2.swgc.mun.ca/animus/Articles/Volume%209/jacobsen.pdf |accessdate=27 May 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108035411/http://www2.swgc.mun.ca/animus/Articles/Volume%209/jacobsen.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThis novel implies it begins in 1992: the cake for Nearly-Headless Nick's 500th deathday party bears the words \"Sir Nicholas De Mimsy Porpington died 31 October 1492\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Rowling|first=J.K.|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets|publisher=Bloomsbury|location=London|year=1998|page=102|isbn=0-7475-3848-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Whited|first=L.|year=2006|title=1492, 1942, 1992: The Theme of Race in the Harry Potter Series|journal=The Looking Glass : New Perspectives on Children's Literature|volume=1|issue=1|url=http://www.lib.latrobe.edu.au/ojs/index.php/tlg/article/view/97/82|accessdate=20 August 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015180112/http://www.lib.latrobe.edu.au/ojs/index.php/tlg/article/view/97/82|archivedate=15 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Connection to ''Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince''===\n''Chamber of Secrets'' has many links with the sixth book of the series, ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]''. In fact, ''Half-Blood Prince'' was the working title of ''Chamber of Secrets'' and Rowling says she originally intended to present some \"crucial pieces of information\" in the second book, but ultimately felt \"this information's proper home was book six\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/news_view.cfm?id=77|title=Title of Book Six: The Truth|last=Rowling|first=J.K.|date=29 June 2004|accessdate=25 May 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423085145/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/news_view.cfm?id=77 <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=23 April 2009}}</ref> Some objects that play significant roles in ''Half-Blood Prince'' first appear in ''Chamber of Secrets'': the [[Hand of Glory]] and the opal necklace that are on sale in [[Borgin and Burkes]]; a Vanishing Cabinet in Hogwarts that is damaged by [[Peeves|Peeves the Poltergeist]]; and [[Tom Riddle's diary]], which is later shown to be a [[Horcrux]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Graeme|title=Re-Read Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets Today! an Unauthorized Guide|publisher=Nimble Books LLC|year=2008|page=74|chapter=Re-reading The Very Secret Diary|isbn=1-934840-72-6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mrvPPS5DXBEC&pg=PA74&dq=%22Chamber+of+Secrets%22+%22Half-Blood+Prince%22+horcrux|accessdate=25 May 2009}}</ref> Additionally, these two novels are the ones with the most focus on Harry's relationship with Ginny Weasley.\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n===Film===\n{{Main|Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)}}\nThe film version of ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' was released in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,389817~1~0~harrypotterandchamber,00.html|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (2002)|last=Schwarzbaum|first=Lisa|date=13 November 2002|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=8 August 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090812235138/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,389817~1~0~harrypotterandchamber,00.html|archivedate=12 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]] directed the film,<ref name=\"tomatoes\"/> and the screenplay was written by [[Steve Kloves]]. It became the third film to exceed $600&nbsp;million in international box office sales, preceded by ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'', released in 1997, and ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (film)|Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]'', released in 2001.<ref name=\"SFSiteNews25Mar2003\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfsite.com/columns/news0303.htm|title=SF Site \u2013 News: 25 March 2003|accessdate=26 May 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080429015040/http://www.sfsite.com/columns/news0303.htm |archivedate = 29 April 2008}}</ref> The film was nominated for a [[Saturn Award]] for the Best Fantasy Film,<ref name=\"SFSiteNews25Mar2003\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saturnawards.org/past.html#fantasy |title=Past Saturn Awards |publisher=Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy & Horror Films |accessdate=26 May 2009 |year=2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110512032708/http://www.saturnawards.org/past.html |archivedate=12 May 2011 }}</ref> According to [[Metacritic]], the film version of ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' received \"generally favourable reviews\" with an average score of 63%,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/video/titles/harrypotterandthechamberofsecrets?q=Harry%20Potter%20and%20the%20Chamber%20of%20Secrets|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (2002): Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=26 May 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090811063436/http://www.metacritic.com/video/titles/harrypotterandthechamberofsecrets?q=Harry%20Potter%20and%20the%20Chamber%20of%20Secrets|archivedate=11 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and another [[Review aggregator|aggregator]], [[Rotten Tomatoes]], gave it a score of 82%.<ref name=\"tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_chamber_of_secrets/ |title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (2002) \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes |work=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=[[Flixster]] |accessdate=26 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204145302/http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_chamber_of_secrets/ |archivedate=4 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n{{Main|Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (video game)}}\n\nFive unique video games by different developers were released between 2002 and 2003 by [[Electronic Arts]], loosely based on the book:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Developer !! Release date !! Platform !! Genre !! [[GameRankings]] !! [[Metacritic]] !! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| [[KnowWonder]] || rowspan=\"7\"| 14 November 2002 || [[Microsoft Windows]] || [[Adventure game|Adventure]]/[[Puzzle video game|puzzle]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 71.46%<ref name=GRPC>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/562014-harry-potter-and-the-chamber-of-secrets/index.html|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets for PC|publisher=GameRankings|accessdate=2014-01-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68hh9MiZ9?url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/562014-harry-potter-and-the-chamber-of-secrets/index.html|archivedate=26 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 77/100<ref name=MCPC>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/harry-potter-and-the-chamber-of-secrets/critic-reviews|title=Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets Critic Reviews for PC|website=Metacritic|accessdate=2014-01-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425023950/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/harry-potter-and-the-chamber-of-secrets/critic-reviews|archivedate=25 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> || &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Argonaut Games|Argonaut]] || [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] || [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 70.50%<ref name=GRPS>